# Strict TypeScript Typing

**ABSOLUTE RULE**: Never use `any`. Never use `as any`. Never use type assertions to bypass the compiler. No exceptions.

## What To Do Instead

### Unknown external data

```typescript
// ❌ FORBIDDEN
const data = response.json() as any;

// ✅ CORRECT
interface ApiResponse { name: string; version: string }
const data: ApiResponse = await response.json();
```

### Missing type definitions

```typescript
// ❌ FORBIDDEN
(module as any).version

// ✅ CORRECT — extend the type
interface ModuleWithVersion extends Module {
  version?: string;
}
```

### Complex generic functions

```typescript
// ❌ FORBIDDEN
function process(input: any): any { ... }

// ✅ CORRECT
function process<T extends Record<string, unknown>>(input: T): T { ... }
```

### Third-party libraries without types

```typescript
// ❌ FORBIDDEN
const lib = require("untyped-lib") as any;

// ✅ CORRECT — create a declaration file (e.g. types/untyped-lib.d.ts)
declare module "untyped-lib" {
  export function doThing(input: string): Promise<Result>;
}
```

### Mongoose/DB model fields

```typescript
// ❌ FORBIDDEN
(version.mfeId as any).name

// ✅ CORRECT — use populate type or interface
interface PopulatedVersion extends IMFEVersion {
  mfeId: IMFEVersion["mfeId"] & { name: string; _id: Types.ObjectId };
}
const version = await MFEVersion.findById(id).populate<{ mfeId: { name: string; _id: Types.ObjectId } }>("mfeId");
```

## Pre-Commit Check

Before every commit, run `tsc --noEmit` on changed packages. Zero errors, zero `any`.

## Fixing Existing `any` Usage

When touching a file that contains `any`, fix every instance in that file before committing. Never add new `any` to the codebase.
